charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story: In 2019, my oldest friend went into hospital with some abdominal pains, and after a rushed surgery was told she had had a rare cancerous tumour removed from her bowel. To say this was a shock to her, and to us, her nearest and dearest, is an understatement. Luckily for us all, Laura’s (or Gibs as she always is to me, it feels weird typing her actual name) Cancer was picked up, operated on and removed, and thanks to our amazing NHS and her own inexhaustible resolve and positive attitude, she has gotten through the months that have passed us since. She has made remarkable changes to her lifestyle and shown bravery that astounds me all the time. Gibs has told us of the incredible support and guidance she has received from her Macmillan nurses in the aftermath of her experience, continuing to this day, and describes them as ‘angels’. It’s with this in mind that I have decided to do this challenge, as a small token of my gratitude to them for caring for someone so important to me. I only started running in Lockdown 1, so although this is no marathon, it feels a bit like one to me! I would be so grateful if you could sponsor me, any amount that you can, to support this amazing cause. I know there are families and friends not as lucky as we are, and the support provided by Macmillan must shine such a light into lives touched by Cancer. I promise I’ll do my very best to honour this amazing service, thank you to anyone who donates xxx
title: Lia's 10 5K in 10 days challenge

pageSummary: We are a team walking 10 million steps by June 1st because In memory of a truly magnificent lady
pageSummaryWhat: We are a team walking 10 million steps by June 1st
pageSummaryWhy: In memory of a truly magnificent lady
story:
In June 2020 our team lost its leader, its gaffer and its friend.  Becki was a true original who was always ready to support, talk and, at times, calm us down.  She had to manage a right rowdy bunch and she did it with humility, heart and humour.

Becki became unwell and suddenly left us out of the blue in June last year.  It has taken time to come to terms with the profound loss we have felt but are now ready to honour her with one of the few things in life she didn't like... walking.

Our team are attempting to walk 10 million steps by the 1st of June 2021. There are 10 of us.  Any donation will always go to the brilliant cause but just to be able to sing her name like this means more than money.  She will forever be missed 🦄
title: QAP's 10 million steps for the gaffer

pageSummary: In memory of my Dad, im giving up Chocolate because He suffered from a heart condition
pageSummaryWhat: In memory of my Dad, im giving up Chocolate
pageSummaryWhy: He suffered from a heart condition
story:
I doing this in memory of my dad who sadly passed away 12 months ago in March after suffering from a heart condition and harding of the arteries for many years.  Increasing falls and finally gangarene meant he ended up in respite and finally in hospital to have a amputation but sadly this was not able to happen as he was not well enough to survive the operation and after 8 short weeks he sadly passed away.  Watching a loved one go through the pain he want through was heart breaking.

  People who know me will also know i have always been a chocoholic and have a really sweet tooth often preferring that to a proper meal.  Giving this up will be hard but its my way of giving a little bit back and hopefully research will continue to help others in the future with heart conditions which includes vascular Dementia which is also close to my heart. Thanks for reading & wish me luck.

pageSummary: I am doing the “leader of snack pack” 30day task because their research helps save lifes like my Milas
pageSummaryWhat: I am doing the “leader of snack pack” 30day task
pageSummaryWhy: their research helps save lifes like my Milas
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. 

Ive chose BHF because my daughter Mila, was born and diagnosed with a rare heart defect called Hypoplastic Right Heart Syndrome - Tricuspid Atresia. 

What this means is her right side of her heart did not develop during pregnancy and her tricuspid valve is underdeveloped. Mila required and still requires lifesaving operations that include open chest surgery on the heart. She will always be under cardiac care through her life.

I’ve chosen to do the “leader of snack pack” challenge,  which means i will give up chocolate, sweets and fizzy drinks for 31days!!

People that know me personally know i do not drink anything except fizzy drink, i consume at-least 5 cans a day and have serious addiction to it. I don't drink water. I also have a really bad sweet tooth! This challenge will most definitely be a big struggle physically and emotionally for me, but im going to do this for my daughter! 

If it wasn’t for the research and science in cardiac care, my daughter along with others would of died at birth! Their research is important to help give babies like my Mila a chance at life.

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. 

£24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target.
title: For my Heart Warrior daughter Mila

story:
Hello All,

As some of you know I've been taking part in DECHOX since 2016 and once again this March I’m chucking the chocolate and going on a DECHOX to help the British Heart Foundation fund its life-saving heart research. 

This charity is one that's of great importance to me as I sadly lost my Grandad in 2019 and I have others who are close to me that I'm also doing this for!

Which means this year's target is my highest yet and I'm more determined than ever...but I need your help!

I need your help and support, on my journey of not eating ANY chocolate, sweets or drinking fizzy drinks for the whole month.

Any money donated by you will help to fund vital life-saving heart research, help to find cures and help provide vital information for heart patients and their families. All the money raised will help make a big difference and it goes directly to the charity itself! 

Please join me by donating as little or as much as you want (you can type the amount you want to donate) to FIGHT FOR EVERY HEARTBEAT.

Despite the pandemic heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our loved ones we need to continue raising money and awareness.


Thankyou <3

pageSummary: I am taking part in Dechox because I would like to help raise money for research!
pageSummaryWhat: I am taking part in Dechox
pageSummaryWhy: I would like to help raise money for research!
story: I stumbled across this opportunity to raise money for British Heart Foundation and I couldn’t pass it up. I imagine most people have had family members affected by heart disease or heart attacks at some point or other and I was shocked to learn that funding has been cut in half recently! So to do my (small) bit I’ve decided to take part in dechox- meaning I’ll be giving up chocolate AND sweets for the full months of February and March! This will be no mean feat for me but I’m going to give it a go as I have lost a few special people in my life due to heart disease and would love to give something to help fund further research. Any small donation would be greatly appreciated

pageSummary: Giving myself a challenge during lockdown because it's worthwhile but will help me too.
pageSummaryWhat: Giving myself a challenge during lockdown
pageSummaryWhy: it's worthwhile but will help me too.
story: The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to many charities being forced to make the devastating decision to cut their research budgets. So the truth is, charities have never needed us so much. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help keep up the pace of progress. I'm going to find my inner willpower to help support the people who need  British Heart Foundation the most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummary: We giving up Chocolate, sweets & fizzy drinks because of the amazing work they do for people in need.
pageSummaryWhat: We giving up Chocolate, sweets & fizzy drinks
pageSummaryWhy: of the amazing work they do for people in need.
story:
We are joining the March 2021 Dechox for the British Heart Foundation. For 31 days we will be giving up Chocolate, sweets & fizzy drinks... which if you know us sounds almost impossible! Heart conditions are something my family have been directly affected by, and raising money for this charity is something that is....well, close to our heart.

Information from the British Heart Foundation - The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most. Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
Hi all, 

Anyone that knows me well will know that I absolutely love chocolate and eat it nearly everyday so for the month of March I will be giving up all chocolate to raise funds for the British Heart Foundation. My target is £150 and I would be so pleased if I could reach that target by the end of March. It's for a great cause and a charity that is known by everyone. Any donations whether it's £1, £5 or £10 will go a long way and are really appreciated. 

I'll post on here every so often to keep you updated on how it's going. 

Thanks alot,                                                              Michelle 😊

pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up chocolate for a whole month
pageSummaryWhy: I want to help a good cause and get motivated.
story:
So if you know me then you know exactly how hard I am going to find this.

It is going to be even harder during the ongoing pandemic, however I am using that to fuel my determination.

Currently I eat chocolate EVERY day and I want to change this habit. I am hoping by doing this challenge, it will not only help a worthy charity but will also help me with my weight loss.

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. story: As a Massive lover of all things sweet I know this dechox month will be a real challenge but a massive accomplishment for me! I love charity and doing good whenever I can, and I also enjoy pushing myself to achieve. After a year of not being able to do anything I want to fill this year with doing as many positive and kind actions as possible. Cutting back on sugary sweet things is one of my New Year's Resolutions for 2021 and this would be a great way to tackle it head on! All whilst raising money for a good cause to really help make a difference. I really appreciate any support you can offer, be it a donation, a share or even just an encouraging message!

pageSummary: I am Dechoxing for the whole month of March because it is time to get healthy! <U+2661>
pageSummaryWhat: I am Dechoxing for the whole month of March
pageSummaryWhy: it is time to get healthy! <U+2661>
story:
Chocoholics unite! 

I have decided to join & give up chocolate, sweets & fizzy drinks for 31 days in March to raise money for life saving research and be part of a movement to beat heartbreak forever!

I lost my dear Dad at the age if 56 years young to a heart attack on 2nd January 2012, so I am dedicating this challenge in honor of him. Every one who knows me knows what a chocoholic & diet coke addict I am, so for 31 days I will give it all up!

Every pound I raise will help fund vital research into heart and circulatory diseases.

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led The British Heart Foundation being forced to make the devastating decision to cut their 2020 research budget in half. 

So the truth is, they've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help them keep up the pace of progress. 

My willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need them most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now!

pageSummary: We are both running 100km in February because we want to be active, so why not for a good cause!
pageSummaryWhat: We are both running 100km in February
pageSummaryWhy: we want to be active, so why not for a good cause!
story:
As a result of the latest developments, we are unable to go ahead with thousands of collections planned across the UK in the coming months. Guide Dogs remains committed to supporting people with sight loss across the UK.

It has never been more important to come together online and support one another. We appreciate times are difficult right now, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their every day. 

By hosting a virtual collection for Guide Dogs, every pound you or your group raises will ensure we can continue to help people with sight loss and feel less alone, now and in the future. It costs £13 a day to support each of our life changing dogs.
title: Theo and Emily both run 100km in February for Guide Dogs

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation. 

Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss. 

We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society. 

A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Since this lockdown is driving me crazy and has me bored out my mind constantly i’ve decided that in order to tackle the boredom the right thing to do is get myself out the house and try to raise a bit of money for charity! 

Basically the aim is that by the time February ends i’ll have walked 170km which is about 6k a day! I know it doesn’t seem like much but honestly the last few weeks i’ve been the laziest wee cow and have spent about 95% of my time in bed🤣

Any money raised will go to the amazing Marie Curie charity which is an organisation that allows nurses to go the extra mile to provide care for those and the family of those suffering from terminal illnesses who need end of life care. My gran spent a short time with Marie Curie nurses before she passed and she spoke so highly of them and always appreciated how much they did for her so I think it’s time to return the favour!💛

Any donations really are appreciated because the money is going to such a great cause🌻

pageSummaryWhy: Set your fitness goal (310,000 steps - 10,000 a...
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
The 20th February is National 'Love your pet' day and we want to help spread some joy whilst raising vital funds for Marie Curie!

- Share your pictures of your pets and a time they have been there for you on Twitter 

- Donate to this page (make sure you include your name/ Twitter handle)

- Be in with the chance of winning a prize! 

Everything you donate will mean the world to Marie Curie and help their frontline nurses continue to provide the care that dying people and their loved ones urgently need.

To see the difference your donations can make, see below:

£1  puts a pen torch in the pocket of a Marie Curie Nurse or doctor, so they can do vital examinations of the people in their care.

£3  pays for heating one of our hospices for an hour, meaning the patients and their families feel warm and comfortable, even on the nippiest of days.

£5  pays for a glass of wine and a nourishing meal for a patient at one of our hospices, because enjoying a favorite tipple brings a smile to people’s faces and is a treat many look forward to.

£20 pays for an hour of expert nursing care and emotional support for someone living with a terminal illness, in the comfort of their own home.

£32 pays for a call to our Support Line, meaning someone in need can pick up the phone and receive practical information and emotional support.

Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story: Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
Finley will be doing 10,000 steps a day in honor of his truly incredible and loving GGPa (Great Grandad) who died of Cancer in 2019.
This will start on the 9th of February and finish on the 9th of March which is his 7th Birthday. Why not start now hey, no need to wait until March!

Finley knows the importance of keeping fit and always encourages us to get our steps up every day! What better way to do some steps and also raise some money in the name of someone that he loved very much. How many people can say that they shared their 4th Birthday Party with their 86 year old GGPa!

Thank you very much to each and every one of you for your support and encouragement.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Dad died in the Marie Curie Hospice Newcastle on November 5th 2023 after a courageous battle with lung cancer. I will never forget the care they gave both him and I in his final days. It is a place has holds a special place in my . 

Running does not come naturally to me and I always said I would never do more than a 10km but here we are. The hospice has never been more important to our City than during Covid-19 and they have lost out on millions of pounds worth of fundraising and they desperately need our help.

A little about the hospice: 

We're here to support people with serious illnesses in the Newcastle area to have the best quality of life possible, whatever that might mean for them.Our hospice team includes doctors, nurses, physiotherapists, social workers and many more, and is supported by over 100 volunteers, who play a vital role in the running of the hospice. Some people stay in our 20-bed in-patient unit, where relatives and friends can visit any time of the day or night, and stay with their loved ones if they wish.Our day therapy unit offers outpatient clinics and a wide range of activities and therapies, including baking, art therapy and relaxation. We also provide support for carers and families, including our social work team who provide emotional and practical advice. Our chaplain is here to provide spiritual care to patients and their loved ones.Thank you for supporting us, and helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in the Newcastle area get the care and support they need.
title: Paula's page
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Mick  Watson

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
RNLI lifeboats in Scotland protect hundreds of communities with a 24-hour search and rescue service. Our volunteer crews rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. 
Scotlands unrivalled coasts and waters are valued by local communities and visitors alike, with millions travelling to enjoy them, and work on them each year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.
Keeping a modern fleet of lifeboats maintained, fuelled and ever ready to go to the rescue from all 46 of the lifeboat stations in Scotland is expensive and we rely entirely on voluntary donations to ensure this service is maintained. It costs an average of £155k to run a lifeboat station in Scotland but with the implications of Covid-19, we havent been able to fundraise as normal to help keep our lifeboats afloat. Can you help?

story:

Scotlands unrivalled coasts and waters are valued by local communities and visitors alike, with millions travelling to enjoy them, and work on them each year. Keeping a modern fleet of lifeboats maintained, fuelled and ever ready to go to the rescue from all 46 of the lifeboat stations in Scotland is expensive and we rely entirely on voluntary donations to ensure this service is maintained. charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
pageSummary: I am running a mile a hour, 15th February for 10hr
pageSummaryWhat: I am running a mile a hour, 15th February for 10hr
story:
Nature needs us. Every second, every minute, every hour. I'm making the most of my time and reaching my potential to do as much as I can for my health and nature. I'm running one mile every hour, maximizing the time in-between to raise money to fight for our world.

I have set myself the challenge of running a mile, every hour to help raise money for WWF. 

I do not mind if you can not give, but if you could give this a share that would be great.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.
